hinkers and practitioners: Mercedes Bidart, Arturo Escobar, Michael Hardt, Greg Lindsay, Jessica Gordon Nembhard, Ai-jen Poo, and Trebor Scholz. Together, they consider how design inspires, invigorates, and sustains contemporary forms of mutualism—including platform cooperatives, digital-first communities, emerging currencies, mutual aid, care networks, social-change movements, and more. From these dialogues emerge powerful visions of futures guided by communal self-determination and collective well-being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDesignxSocial aspects. 0aMutualism. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aAi-jen Poo.  aArturo Escobar.  aCarehaus.  aGreg Lindsay.  aJessica Gordon Nembhard.  aMercedes Bidart.  aMichael Hardt.  aTrevor Scholz.  aactivism.  aarchitecture.  aart.  acare networks.  acommunity.  adesign.  alabor organizing.  amutual aid.  amutualism.  asocial change movements.  asocial change.  asocial practice.  asolidarity.  aurban planning.  aurban studies.1 aBidart, Mercedes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscobar, Arturo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardt, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJahn, Marisa Morán, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJahn, Marisa Morán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindsay, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNembhard, Jessica Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoo, Ai-jen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScholz, Trebor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSegal, Rafi, econtrib